Unlike ARIMA, the SVM model does not yield a linear equation with
clear-cut coefficients for each input variable. However, it fits a
\textbf{nonlinear surface} that attempts to minimize prediction error
within the specified  tolerance.

The support vector coefficients (e.g., -1.000, -0.9517, etc.) indicate
the contributions of these observations in shaping the regression
function. The model's structure allows it to effectively model nonlinear
interactions between \textbf{Inflation}, \textbf{Date}, \textbf{M2}, and
\textbf{Unemployment}, which may be too complex for a simple linear
model.

This model is expected to perform well on capturing subtle nonlinear
patterns, especially when economic relationships deviate from linear
assumptions.

\hypertarget{random-forest-regression-model}{%
\subsubsection{Random Forest Regression
Model}\label{random-forest-regression-model}}

Random Forest is a tree-based ensemble learning method that builds
multiple decision trees during training and outputs the average
prediction of the individual trees. It handles \textbf{nonlinearities},
\textbf{interactions}, and \textbf{multicollinearity} well without
requiring strong parametric assumptions.

\hypertarget{general-logic-of-random-forest-regression}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{General Logic of Random Forest
Regression}}{General Logic of Random Forest Regression}}\label{general-logic-of-random-forest-regression}}

There is no fixed "equation" for Random Forest like linear models.
Instead, each decision tree splits the feature space into distinct
regions and assigns a prediction based on training data in those
regions. The final prediction is the \textbf{average} of predictions
across all trees:

