\hypertarget{interpretation-and-predictions-1}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{Interpretation and
Predictions}}{Interpretation and Predictions}}\label{interpretation-and-predictions-1}}

The Random Forest model captures \textbf{nonlinear and interaction
effects} automatically. For instance, it can detect if the effect of
unemployment on inflation depends on the money supply or changes over
time, without explicitly modeling these interactions.

Since it does not produce an algebraic equation, interpretability is
lower than that of ARIMA. However, the predictive power is usually
higher, particularly in data with complex structure.

The model assigns higher importance to M2, which suggests that changes
in the money supply are a significant predictor of inflation in this
dataset.

\hypertarget{conclusion-of-model-estimations}{%
\subsubsection{Conclusion of Model
Estimations}\label{conclusion-of-model-estimations}}

The ARIMA model offers a \textbf{statistically interpretable} equation
rooted in time series theory. It reveals that past inflation and
temporal trends play a significant role. The SVM model adds a
\textbf{nonlinear layer}, learning subtle patterns via support vectors
and kernel functions, while the Random Forest model provides the
\textbf{most flexible predictive structure}, capable of capturing
nonlinearities and variable interactions without predefined form.

Each model has its strengths:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  ARIMA: Best for \textbf{interpretable temporal relationships}.
\item
  SVM: Suitable for \textbf{nonlinear regression} with moderate
  complexity.
\item
  Random Forest: Ideal for \textbf{high-performance, flexible
  predictions} where interpretability is less critical.
\end{itemize}

